    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for explaining. so if the temp is too low it stays pale, but what's the upper limit? like is there a specific point where it stops being \"just browning\" and actually starts to taste burnt or bitter? i'm trying to get the timing right for a sourdough i'm working on.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The upper limit, where the Maillard reaction tips into the territory of \"burnt\" and bitter, is when you start breaking down those desirable compounds into acrid ones. This usually happens when the temperature gets too high, pushing past the sweet spot and into the realm of caramelization gone wrong, which is often around 350°F (175°C) and higher, depending on the specific ingredients. For your sourdough, you want to aim for that perfect, deep golden-brown, which is the peak of the reaction before the flavor profile turns sour or smoky from charring. Keep an eye on the crust color, not just the clock, for the best results!",
      "source": "target",
